WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.610 --> 00:00:04.840
We can do the following problem.
 

00:00:04.840 --> 00:00:10.357
You give me any number of
charges which are fixed,

00:00:10.357 --> 00:00:12.610
anywhere you want.
 

00:00:12.610 --> 00:00:13.870
So here they are.
 

00:00:13.870 --> 00:00:16.234
Here's one guy
q_1,

00:00:16.234 --> 00:00:20.220
here's q_2,
here's q_3.

00:00:20.220 --> 00:00:23.889
And instead of these discrete
charges, you may have a line

00:00:23.889 --> 00:00:26.980
charge too, maybe λ
coulombs per meter.

00:00:26.980 --> 00:00:30.140
That guy is here.
 

00:00:30.140 --> 00:00:31.340
They are fixed.
 

00:00:31.340 --> 00:00:35.280
They are not dynamical.
 

00:00:35.280 --> 00:00:39.954
The object of interest to us is
this charge q,

00:00:39.954 --> 00:00:43.820
which can actually move,
allowed to move.

00:00:43.820 --> 00:00:48.236
The question we ask is,
do we know what this charge

00:00:48.236 --> 00:00:49.120
will do?
 

00:00:49.120 --> 00:00:51.150
And the answer is,
yes, we know what it will do,

00:00:51.150 --> 00:00:54.567
because if it's sitting here
and we have already computed the

00:00:54.567 --> 00:00:57.175
electric field everywhere--
you know how to compute

00:00:57.175 --> 00:00:57.840
electric field.
 

00:00:57.840 --> 00:01:00.771
Add the field due to this one,
that one, that one,

00:01:00.771 --> 00:01:01.429
add that.
 

00:01:01.429 --> 00:01:04.968
That is some electric field
sitting here.

00:01:04.968 --> 00:01:08.593
Then we know,
the force on this charge we're

00:01:08.593 --> 00:01:11.710
interested in,
this q times the

00:01:11.710 --> 00:01:15.840
electric field at the location
of the charge.

00:01:15.840 --> 00:01:18.763
So at every instant,
we know what force is acting on

00:01:18.763 --> 00:01:19.049
it.
 

00:01:19.049 --> 00:01:24.456
Then from Newton's law,
that will give me the rate of

00:01:24.456 --> 00:01:28.720
change of velocity or the
acceleration.

00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:30.970
You can write it either way.
 

00:01:30.970 --> 00:01:33.721
That's all I need,
because using that I can find

00:01:33.721 --> 00:01:35.714
out the new position,
new velocity,

00:01:35.714 --> 00:01:36.300
right?
 

00:01:36.300 --> 00:01:39.959
The acceleration tells you,
if you wait 1 nanosecond,

00:01:39.959 --> 00:01:43.519
you go to this place,
because the initial velocity,

00:01:43.519 --> 00:01:45.867
I can predict where it will be,
and because you know the

00:01:45.867 --> 00:01:48.732
acceleration,
I know what velocity it will

00:01:48.732 --> 00:01:49.200
have.
 

00:01:49.200 --> 00:01:53.420
Then I keep on updating it and
I get my trajectory.

00:01:53.420 --> 00:01:57.069
Student:  I think it
should be dt squared.

00:01:57.069 --> 00:02:02.739
Prof: Yes, thank you.
 

00:02:02.739 --> 00:02:06.590
So everyone understands this is
how you proceed.

00:02:06.590 --> 00:02:09.127
This charge will of course push
those guys, but we're not

00:02:09.127 --> 00:02:11.030
worried, because we don't let
them move.

00:02:11.030 --> 00:02:13.360
They are just fixed.
 

00:02:13.360 --> 00:02:17.520
And if there are much such
charges, we can find what they

00:02:17.520 --> 00:02:21.236
all do in this environment,
which is the background

00:02:21.236 --> 00:02:22.650
electric field.
 

00:02:22.650 --> 00:02:24.919
That's all we can do right now,
this is electrostatics.

00:02:24.919 --> 00:02:27.401
In the real world,
everybody is moving and all

00:02:27.401 --> 00:02:29.664
kinds of stuff happens,
but you cannot use

00:02:29.664 --> 00:02:31.210
electrostatics for that.
 

00:02:31.210 --> 00:02:34.733
This asymmetry between the
background and the test charge

00:02:34.733 --> 00:02:37.878
that we are studying is in the
static situation.

00:02:37.878 --> 00:02:41.370
Guys that move and guys that
don't.

00:02:41.370 --> 00:02:43.340
Now this is something you could
have done on the first day,

00:02:43.340 --> 00:02:46.377
because I think on the very
first day I told you about

00:02:46.377 --> 00:02:49.300
Coulomb's law and the principle
of superposition.

00:02:49.300 --> 00:02:52.666
If you put them together,
you know the force on a charge

00:02:52.666 --> 00:02:53.340
q.
 

00:02:53.340 --> 00:02:57.210
Then you use F = ma,
you predict its trajectory.

00:02:57.210 --> 00:02:59.711
But in principle,
that's all you need to do

00:02:59.711 --> 00:03:02.655
electrostatic problems,
but in practice you want to

00:03:02.655 --> 00:03:04.620
clean up the machinery a little
bit,

00:03:04.620 --> 00:03:07.188
make it more efficient.
 

00:03:07.188 --> 00:03:08.900
For example,
we found Gauss's law.

00:03:08.900 --> 00:03:11.157
Gauss's law follows from
Coulomb's law,

00:03:11.157 --> 00:03:13.120
but we found it's quite useful.
 

00:03:13.120 --> 00:03:14.979
For example,
if we give you a ball of

00:03:14.979 --> 00:03:17.873
charge, spherical charge,
going back to Coulomb's law and

00:03:17.873 --> 00:03:19.889
first principles is very
difficult.

00:03:19.889 --> 00:03:21.938
But if you use Gauss's law and
the symmetries,

00:03:21.938 --> 00:03:23.959
you're able to find the
electric field around the

00:03:23.959 --> 00:03:26.465
sphere,
or an infinitely long cylinder,

00:03:26.465 --> 00:03:30.030
or an infinite plane or simple
geometries like that.

00:03:30.030 --> 00:03:31.997
So it's not enough to say
"I've got the basic

00:03:31.997 --> 00:03:32.720
equations."
 

00:03:32.720 --> 00:03:36.812
You always want to see if there
are ways to speed up the

00:03:36.812 --> 00:03:39.788
computation to make it more
efficient.

00:03:39.788 --> 00:03:49.645
So let me remind you what we
did in the first part of the

00:03:49.645 --> 00:03:51.229
course.
 

00:03:51.229 --> 00:03:55.205
There, if you have the
following question - here's a

00:03:55.205 --> 00:03:59.712
spring and here's a mass,
the spring likes to have that

00:03:59.712 --> 00:04:04.598
length and I pulled it to way
over there and I released it,

00:04:04.598 --> 00:04:06.539
and right now it happens to be
here,

00:04:06.539 --> 00:04:08.508
going at some speed.
 

00:04:08.508 --> 00:04:12.870
I want to know what velocity it
will have when it is here,

00:04:12.870 --> 00:04:14.878
so this position is
x_1,

00:04:14.878 --> 00:04:16.319
this speed is
v_1,

00:04:16.319 --> 00:04:18.028
this position is
x_2.

00:04:18.028 --> 00:04:20.569
I want to know
v_2.

00:04:20.569 --> 00:04:22.860
That's a reasonable thing you
can ask.

00:04:22.860 --> 00:04:27.608
Unlike the electric force,
the force on this mass is due

00:04:27.608 --> 00:04:28.990
to the spring.
 

00:04:28.990 --> 00:04:31.790
Apart from that,
it's the same situation.

00:04:31.790 --> 00:04:35.379
So one way to do that is to
say, I know F = ma,

00:04:35.379 --> 00:04:38.129
so the instant you start the
problem here,

00:04:38.129 --> 00:04:40.980
I know the acceleration because
the force of the spring is

00:04:40.980 --> 00:04:42.579
-k times x_1.
 

00:04:42.579 --> 00:04:45.230
Once I know the force,
I know the acceleration.

00:04:45.230 --> 00:04:47.440
I can find the new velocity,
new position,

00:04:47.440 --> 00:04:50.310
keep on doing it,
or I can solve the equation,

00:04:50.310 --> 00:04:53.899
d^(2)x/dt^(2) is
−kx/m,

00:04:53.899 --> 00:04:55.750
and I can eventually end up
here.

00:04:55.750 --> 00:04:59.430
Then I can find the velocity
here.

00:04:59.430 --> 00:05:05.607
But we all know that in this
problem, there's a shortcut,

00:05:05.607 --> 00:05:06.490
right?
 

00:05:06.490 --> 00:05:07.490
Yes?
 

00:05:07.490 --> 00:05:13.329
Anybody in the last row want to
tell me what the shortcut is?

00:05:13.329 --> 00:05:14.569
Yes?
 

00:05:14.569 --> 00:05:16.670
Student:  You can use
conservation of energy.

00:05:16.670 --> 00:05:19.389
Prof: Conservation of
energy.

00:05:19.389 --> 00:05:23.975
So conservation of energy is a
consequence of Newton's laws and

00:05:23.975 --> 00:05:26.490
certain properties of the force.
 

00:05:26.490 --> 00:05:29.949
I'm going to remind you how
it's done.

00:05:29.949 --> 00:05:33.524
One attitude I could take is,
you've already done this

00:05:33.524 --> 00:05:37.706
before, but usually it's better
to make sure that you're all on

00:05:37.706 --> 00:05:40.000
the same page when we do this.
 

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.480
So let me remind you how it
works there.

00:05:43.480 --> 00:05:52.220
You go to Newton's laws and we
write m dv/dt =

00:05:52.220 --> 00:05:53.850
F.
 

00:05:53.850 --> 00:05:54.990
It's all in one dimension
though.

00:05:54.990 --> 00:05:58.339
I'm moving just along the line.
 

00:05:58.339 --> 00:06:05.610
Then I multiply both sides by
v.

00:06:05.610 --> 00:06:09.805
On the left hand side,
if you know basic calculus,

00:06:09.805 --> 00:06:12.802
this is really
d/dt of

00:06:12.802 --> 00:06:17.170
mv^(2)/2,
by the chain rule of calculus.

00:06:17.170 --> 00:06:19.810
The d/dt derivative is
the v derivative,

00:06:19.810 --> 00:06:22.452
followed by the derivative of
v with respect to

00:06:22.452 --> 00:06:23.100
t.
 

00:06:23.100 --> 00:06:25.740
v derivative will give
you mv and then there is

00:06:25.740 --> 00:06:26.050
that.
 

00:06:26.050 --> 00:06:33.949
This becomes F
dx/dt.

00:06:33.949 --> 00:06:36.970
This means in every tiny
instant of time,

00:06:36.970 --> 00:06:41.475
the force times the change in
the position is equal to the

00:06:41.475 --> 00:06:46.964
change in this quantity,
which we know is called kinetic

00:06:46.964 --> 00:06:47.829
energy.
 

00:06:47.829 --> 00:06:51.449
So if you multiply both sides
by dt,

00:06:51.449 --> 00:06:54.795
then you find this relation,
and if you add up all the

00:06:54.795 --> 00:06:56.843
changes,
we get this relation,

00:06:56.843 --> 00:07:00.776
m--so let's see what we
are integrating from a starting

00:07:00.776 --> 00:07:04.129
point to an ending point and
some starting time,

00:07:04.129 --> 00:07:06.149
ending time.
 

00:07:06.149 --> 00:07:09.663
We get
mv_2^(2)/2 -

00:07:09.663 --> 00:07:13.377
mv_1^(2)/2 =
integral

00:07:13.377 --> 00:07:18.899
f(x)dx from
x_1 to

00:07:18.899 --> 00:07:21.610
x_2.
 

00:07:21.610 --> 00:07:29.370
And this is called the work
energy theorem.

00:07:29.370 --> 00:07:32.757
The work energy theorem tells
you something you may expect,

00:07:32.757 --> 00:07:36.261
namely, when a force acts on a
body, it's going to accelerate

00:07:36.261 --> 00:07:36.670
it.
 

00:07:36.670 --> 00:07:38.906
It's going to accelerate it,
it's going to change the

00:07:38.906 --> 00:07:39.379
velocity.
 

00:07:39.379 --> 00:07:41.497
You're going to ask,
"How much velocity change

00:07:41.497 --> 00:07:43.660
do I get for a certain action of
the force?"

00:07:43.660 --> 00:07:46.060
and the statement is,
the force pushes the body from

00:07:46.060 --> 00:07:48.319
x_1 to
x_2,

00:07:48.319 --> 00:07:54.220
then this is the change in this
quantity called kinetic energy.

00:07:54.220 --> 00:07:57.300
This is true no matter what the
force is.

00:07:57.300 --> 00:08:00.331
It's true for friction,
it's true for spring,

00:08:00.331 --> 00:08:04.120
it's true for everything,
because Newton's law is always

00:08:04.120 --> 00:08:04.810
valid.
 

00:08:04.810 --> 00:08:08.418
But if you want to extract from
this a law of conservation of

00:08:08.418 --> 00:08:12.266
energy, you have to do a certain
manipulation and that's what I'm

00:08:12.266 --> 00:08:13.588
going to describe.
 

00:08:13.588 --> 00:08:19.403
So let's go back here and try
to extract from it a law of

00:08:19.403 --> 00:08:22.000
conservation of energy.
 

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:25.495
So I'm going to write here
k_2 -

00:08:25.495 --> 00:08:30.230
k_1 is integral
F(x) dx,

00:08:30.230 --> 00:08:36.690
from x_1 to
x_2.

00:08:36.690 --> 00:08:40.532
Now it's a fundamental result
in calculus that integral of any

00:08:40.532 --> 00:08:44.186
function of x from the
point x_1 to

00:08:44.186 --> 00:08:47.147
the point x_2
can be written as

00:08:47.147 --> 00:08:51.620
G(x_2) -
G(x_1),

00:08:51.620 --> 00:08:57.889
where G is any function
whose derivative is the F

00:08:57.889 --> 00:08:59.710
I'm integrating.
 

00:08:59.710 --> 00:09:02.256
For example,
if F = x,

00:09:02.256 --> 00:09:06.259
G = x^(2)/2,
because derivative

00:09:06.259 --> 00:09:09.080
x^(2)/2 is x.
 

00:09:09.080 --> 00:09:10.668
In fact, it's not just
x^(2)/2 .

00:09:10.668 --> 00:09:14.160
You can add x^(2)/2 a
constant, but the constant is

00:09:14.160 --> 00:09:16.856
not important,
because they'll cancel between

00:09:16.856 --> 00:09:17.960
this and this.
 

00:09:17.960 --> 00:09:21.101
So you can pick the solution
without a constant,

00:09:21.101 --> 00:09:21.570
okay?
 

00:09:21.570 --> 00:09:24.460
Now what does that mean?
 

00:09:24.460 --> 00:09:29.336
Let's rearrange the expression
so I get K_2

00:09:29.336 --> 00:09:32.559
−
G(x_2) =

00:09:32.559 --> 00:09:37.850
K_1 −
G(x_1).

00:09:37.850 --> 00:09:41.253
That tells you the combination
K - G does not

00:09:41.253 --> 00:09:44.480
change as the particle moves,
but this doesn't look very

00:09:44.480 --> 00:09:45.009
nice.
 

00:09:45.009 --> 00:09:48.293
We want to get the old law of
conservation of energy in the

00:09:48.293 --> 00:09:49.200
standard form.
 

00:09:49.200 --> 00:09:51.600
You define the function
U(x),

00:09:51.600 --> 00:09:53.830
you simply - this
G(x).

00:09:53.830 --> 00:09:55.440
It's a very trivial change.
 

00:09:55.440 --> 00:09:57.578
Then you can say
K_2

00:09:57.578 --> 00:10:00.669
U(x_2) =
K_1

00:10:00.669 --> 00:10:06.629
U(x_1),
and that is the energy that

00:10:06.629 --> 00:10:10.450
does not change with time.
 

00:10:10.450 --> 00:10:15.298
So the relation between
U, which is called the

00:10:15.298 --> 00:10:18.191
potential energy,
and the force,

00:10:18.191 --> 00:10:20.149
is the following.
 

00:10:20.149 --> 00:10:26.220
The force is - the derivative
of the potential energy.

00:10:26.220 --> 00:10:30.403
The - came because G is
the integral of F,

00:10:30.403 --> 00:10:33.979
but U is -G,
so that this formula,

00:10:33.979 --> 00:10:36.870
this means you have this
relation.

00:10:36.870 --> 00:10:39.774
And you can also say
U(x_2)

00:10:39.774 --> 00:10:41.926
−
U(x_1)

00:10:41.926 --> 00:10:44.657
with an integral of
F(x) dx

00:10:44.657 --> 00:10:47.970
from x_1 to
x_2,

00:10:47.970 --> 00:10:49.620
there's a - sign here.
 

00:10:49.620 --> 00:10:54.846
Again, the - sign is present
because F is defined to

00:10:54.846 --> 00:10:57.908
be - the derivative of U.
 

00:10:57.908 --> 00:11:00.442
So you can go back and forth
from potential to force and

00:11:00.442 --> 00:11:01.408
force to potential.
 

00:11:01.408 --> 00:11:03.513
If you knew the force,
you can integrate it to get the

00:11:03.513 --> 00:11:03.990
potential.
 

00:11:03.990 --> 00:11:06.187
If you knew the potential,
you can differentiate it to get

00:11:06.187 --> 00:11:07.885
the force,
and more importantly,

00:11:07.885 --> 00:11:10.110
you have this great
conservation law,

00:11:10.110 --> 00:11:12.288
which is very helpful in the
spring problem,

00:11:12.288 --> 00:11:14.080
because if you know the
potential energy,

00:11:14.080 --> 00:11:16.528
once and for all,
it's kx^(2)/2,

00:11:16.528 --> 00:11:18.418
you balance the kinetic and the
potential,

00:11:18.418 --> 00:11:23.500
you can find the velocity at
one other point.

00:11:23.500 --> 00:11:27.538
Now why doesn't this work for
friction?

00:11:27.538 --> 00:11:30.029
Friction is the one dimensional
force.

00:11:30.029 --> 00:11:31.070
Yes?
 

00:11:31.070 --> 00:11:32.629
Student:  It's not
conservative.

00:11:32.629 --> 00:11:33.870
Prof: It's not
conservative.

00:11:33.870 --> 00:11:35.009
It's just a definition.
 

00:11:35.009 --> 00:11:39.269
But what's wrong with my
argument?

00:11:39.269 --> 00:11:43.429
Where in this argument does it
fail?

00:11:43.429 --> 00:11:44.970
It looks like any function--yes?
 

00:11:44.970 --> 00:11:47.054
Student:  Because the
direction of the force depends

00:11:47.054 --> 00:11:48.710
on the direction that the
particle's moving.

00:11:48.710 --> 00:11:50.190
Prof: Very good.
 

00:11:50.190 --> 00:11:54.296
The point is that frictional
force is not a function just of

00:11:54.296 --> 00:11:55.409
your location.
 

00:11:55.409 --> 00:11:57.960
It depends on your velocity.
 

00:11:57.960 --> 00:12:02.101
In other words,
whereas the spring will always

00:12:02.101 --> 00:12:06.019
exert a force -kx--
if you are displaced to the

00:12:06.019 --> 00:12:08.100
right by an x,
it exerts a force

00:12:08.100 --> 00:12:11.200
-kx--whether or not
you're moving to the right,

00:12:11.200 --> 00:12:13.970
away from the equilibrium or
towards it.

00:12:13.970 --> 00:12:16.331
Thus given x,
it gives you a given force,

00:12:16.331 --> 00:12:17.940
but friction is not like that.
 

00:12:17.940 --> 00:12:20.250
Friction does not have a
definite direction.

00:12:20.250 --> 00:12:23.450
The only thing friction wants
to do is to slow you down.

00:12:23.450 --> 00:12:25.778
If you want to go right,
it wants to act left.

00:12:25.778 --> 00:12:28.399
If you want to go left,
it wants to act right.

00:12:28.399 --> 00:12:31.340
I will resist all political
analogies.

00:12:31.340 --> 00:12:35.616
I'll just point out to you that
friction does not have a

00:12:35.616 --> 00:12:37.769
definite sign,
therefore it's not a function

00:12:37.769 --> 00:12:38.947
of x,
but as she said,

00:12:38.947 --> 00:12:41.379
it's a function of x and
of x dot,

00:12:41.379 --> 00:12:42.750
which is the velocity.
 

00:12:42.750 --> 00:12:45.129
So it doesn't have a unique
answer.

00:12:45.129 --> 00:12:47.820
That does not mean you cannot
find the work due to friction.

00:12:47.820 --> 00:12:50.160
If you know it's moving to the
right, then the force is to the

00:12:50.160 --> 00:12:50.428
left.
 

00:12:50.428 --> 00:12:53.802
You can integrate that force,
as long as it is moving to the

00:12:53.802 --> 00:12:54.259
right.
 

00:12:54.259 --> 00:12:55.851
But if it's going right,
left, right,

00:12:55.851 --> 00:12:58.019
left and oscillating,
then you cannot integrate it

00:12:58.019 --> 00:12:58.950
once and for all.
 

00:12:58.950 --> 00:13:02.240
That way doesn't work for
friction.

00:13:02.240 --> 00:13:05.474
Now here's an even more
powerful example of the law of

00:13:05.474 --> 00:13:07.000
conservation of energy.
 

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:15.860
You have this famous roller
