and I'll come to that in a

00:14:03.035 --> 00:14:03.629
moment.
 

00:14:03.629 --> 00:14:07.528
Then we say kinetic potential
is kinetic potential in the

00:14:07.528 --> 00:14:12.037
beginning and at the end,
and we can simply find the

00:14:12.037 --> 00:14:17.250
velocity here if you knew the
potential energy here.

00:14:17.250 --> 00:14:20.470
All right, so the law of
conservation of energy is also a

00:14:20.470 --> 00:14:23.172
very profound result,
which has survived all the

00:14:23.172 --> 00:14:25.298
revolutions of quantum
mechanics.

00:14:25.298 --> 00:14:28.048
After quantum mechanics,
we don't like to think in terms

00:14:28.048 --> 00:14:31.250
of force, and we don't like to
think in terms of trajectories.

00:14:31.250 --> 00:14:33.808
You don't even know for sure
where the particle is.

00:14:33.808 --> 00:14:37.429
But amazingly,
the total energy is always

00:14:37.429 --> 00:14:40.779
conserved in the problems we
study.

00:14:40.779 --> 00:14:44.383
So the law of conservation of
energy is very profound and it's

00:14:44.383 --> 00:14:46.509
also very useful for
computations.

00:14:46.509 --> 00:14:50.495
Now the next question I have
is, if I go to two

00:14:50.495 --> 00:14:55.259
dimensions--and it's the same as
in three dimensions.

00:14:55.259 --> 00:14:58.554
I'm just going to go to two
dimensions--what does it take to

00:14:58.554 --> 00:15:00.788
get the law of conservation of
energy?

00:15:00.788 --> 00:15:04.235
So I'm going to mimic this
derivation in 2D and see if I

00:15:04.235 --> 00:15:07.179
can pull out a law of
conservation of energy.

00:15:07.179 --> 00:15:09.528
So here's what I will do.
 

00:15:09.528 --> 00:15:13.855
So in two dimensions,
let me start this time with the

00:15:13.855 --> 00:15:15.269
kinetic energy.
 

00:15:15.269 --> 00:15:18.163
Kinetic energy is
½mv^(2),

00:15:18.163 --> 00:15:19.926
but
v has got 2 components,

00:15:19.926 --> 00:15:21.975
x and y,
therefore it's

00:15:21.975 --> 00:15:24.750
½mvx^(2)
vy^(2),

00:15:24.750 --> 00:15:28.530
but I'm going to write this
½m

00:15:28.530 --> 00:15:30.730
v⋅v.
 

00:15:30.730 --> 00:15:34.470
Then let me ask,
what's the rate of change of

00:15:34.470 --> 00:15:36.340
this kinetic energy?
 

00:15:36.340 --> 00:15:38.710
You've got to take derivatives.
 

00:15:38.710 --> 00:15:41.077
Now you may be a little queasy
about taking derivatives from

00:15:41.077 --> 00:15:43.086
this dot product,
but you can check by expanding

00:15:43.086 --> 00:15:45.250
the component,
just like ordinary product,

00:15:45.250 --> 00:15:48.460
and you can take derivative of
this guy times that guy,

00:15:48.460 --> 00:15:50.548
derivative of that guy times
this guy,

00:15:50.548 --> 00:15:54.375
and they will both be the same,
and you will find it's equal to

00:15:54.375 --> 00:16:03.850
m dv/dt,
which is the force.

00:16:03.850 --> 00:16:09.950
I'm sorry.
 

00:16:09.950 --> 00:16:14.659
Let me erase this.
 

00:16:14.659 --> 00:16:20.698
It's not m dv/dt;
