00:16:20.698 --> 00:16:24.788
⋅v.
 

00:16:24.788 --> 00:16:27.895
So if you integrate this,
cancel the dt and add

00:16:27.895 --> 00:16:30.500
all the changes,
you will find

00:16:30.500 --> 00:16:36.695
K_2 -
K_1 is m

00:16:36.695 --> 00:16:45.259
times dr--
let me see--I'm sorry.

00:16:45.259 --> 00:16:47.936
I want to keep the
dv/dt here,

00:16:47.936 --> 00:16:51.669
then I want to write this
v as dr/dt.

00:16:51.669 --> 00:16:52.100
That's right.
 

00:16:52.100 --> 00:16:54.519
So let me do the following,
excuse me.

00:16:54.519 --> 00:16:55.418
Let me do it again.
 

00:16:55.418 --> 00:17:03.495
dK/dt = ma
times v and v is

00:17:03.495 --> 00:17:06.410
dr/dt.
 

00:17:06.410 --> 00:17:10.855
Now we cancel the dts
and we write the change in

00:17:10.855 --> 00:17:15.465
K as K_2
- K_1 =

00:17:15.465 --> 00:17:19.006
integral of
F⋅dr from the

00:17:19.006 --> 00:17:22.382
starting point
r_1 to the

00:17:22.382 --> 00:17:25.838
ending point
r_2.

00:17:25.838 --> 00:17:28.586
In other words,
the change in kinetic energy in

00:17:28.586 --> 00:17:31.573
one dimension is just force
times distance for tiny

00:17:31.573 --> 00:17:32.410
distances.
 

00:17:32.410 --> 00:17:35.098
In higher dimensions,
like in 2 dimensions,

00:17:35.098 --> 00:17:38.464
if the particle is moving in
the 2 dimensional plane along

00:17:38.464 --> 00:17:41.240
some path and it moves a
distance dr,

00:17:41.240 --> 00:17:44.450
and at that point,
the force is in that direction,

00:17:44.450 --> 00:17:46.909
you should not simply take the
product of the length of the

00:17:46.909 --> 00:17:48.690
force times the length of the
distance,

00:17:48.690 --> 00:17:52.859
but that times the cosine of
the angle.

00:17:52.859 --> 00:17:54.108
Why should it take that?
 

00:17:54.108 --> 00:17:56.636
Because that's what gives you
the rate of change of kinetic

00:17:56.636 --> 00:17:57.029
energy.
 

00:17:57.029 --> 00:18:00.230
Just go to the kinetic energy
and it suggests to you that you

00:18:00.230 --> 00:18:02.900
take this product and define it
to be the work,

00:18:02.900 --> 00:18:05.720
because if you define it that
way, just like in 1D,

00:18:05.720 --> 00:18:10.549
the work done by the force will
be the change in kinetic energy.

00:18:10.549 --> 00:18:11.740
You guys with me now?
 

00:18:11.740 --> 00:18:15.640
In spite of this little mess up
here, this ma is my force.

00:18:15.640 --> 00:18:17.180
The dts got canceled.
 

00:18:17.180 --> 00:18:21.071
The dK is added up to
K_2 -

00:18:21.071 --> 00:18:24.808
K_1 and this is
the integral.

00:18:24.808 --> 00:18:29.759
All right, so now it looks
pretty good, except for the

00:18:29.759 --> 00:18:31.160
complication.
 

00:18:31.160 --> 00:18:32.920
You have a dot product here.
 

00:18:32.920 --> 00:18:36.502
You have this nice result that
K_2 -

00:18:36.502 --> 00:18:40.292
K_1 is the
integral F⋅dr

00:18:40.292 --> 00:18:44.288
from r_1 to
r_2.

00:18:44.288 --> 00:18:46.035
So let's imagine where
r_1 and

00:18:46.035 --> 00:18:47.058
r_2 are.
 

00:18:47.058 --> 00:18:52.336
This is say where you started,
and maybe you ended up here at

00:18:52.336 --> 00:18:54.358
r_2.
 

00:18:54.358 --> 00:18:56.922
You've just got to integrate
this F from

00:18:56.922 --> 00:18:59.538
r_1 to
r_2.

00:18:59.538 --> 00:19:01.618
Let's imagine there is no
friction.

00:19:01.618 --> 00:19:04.690
Let's imagine F depends
only on the position.

00:19:04.690 --> 00:19:08.289
What's my problem now?
 

00:19:08.289 --> 00:19:13.450
What problem do we have?
 

00:19:13.450 --> 00:19:14.750
Yes?
 

00:19:14.750 --> 00:19:16.502
Student:  _______ going
from r_2 to

00:19:16.502 --> 00:19:17.440
r_1 _______.
 

00:19:17.440 --> 00:19:19.104
Prof: No,
this integral gives me no

00:19:19.104 --> 00:19:19.470
choice.
 

00:19:19.470 --> 00:19:23.422
I must go from
r_1 to

00:19:23.422 --> 00:19:25.880
r_2.
 

00:19:25.880 --> 00:19:27.769
Anybody know what's the problem?
 

00:19:27.769 --> 00:19:28.740
Yes?
 

00:19:28.740 --> 00:19:30.970
Student:  Your path.
 

00:19:30.970 --> 00:19:31.858
Prof: Your path.
 

00:19:31.858 --> 00:19:34.673
See, in 1 dimension,
if I want to go from here to

00:19:34.673 --> 00:19:36.549
there, I have no choice,
okay?

00:19:36.549 --> 00:19:38.920
Just move along that line.
 

00:19:38.920 --> 00:19:40.971
In 2 dimensions,
if you want to go from one

00:19:40.971 --> 00:19:43.170
point to another,
I can think of many ways.

00:19:43.170 --> 00:19:46.700
You can do that,
you can take the straight line

00:19:46.700 --> 00:19:49.769
path, or you can take some other
path.

00:19:49.769 --> 00:19:52.548
That's an ambiguity we have in
higher dimensions.

00:19:52.548 --> 00:19:55.890
So even though the work energy
theorem is valid,

00:19:55.890 --> 00:19:58.488
and no matter which path you
take, the work done by the force

00:19:58.488 --> 00:20:00.220
will be the change in kinetic
energy,

00:20:00.220 --> 00:20:05.727
this is not in general equal to
some function at

00:20:05.727 --> 00:20:10.180
r_1 - some
function at

00:20:10.180 --> 00:20:13.108
r_2.
 

00:20:13.108 --> 00:20:16.099
Because if it had this form,
we are done.

00:20:16.099 --> 00:20:16.778
You agree?
 

00:20:16.778 --> 00:20:19.133
If it had this form,
then again you write

00:20:19.133 --> 00:20:21.321
K_2 
U_2 =

00:20:21.321 --> 00:20:23.838
K_1
U_1.

00:20:23.838 --> 00:20:26.240
But no one's telling you that
is true.

00:20:26.240 --> 00:20:29.528
If it was true,
you are in business.

00:20:29.528 --> 00:20:32.880
But it's a very unreasonable
thing to ask of this force,

00:20:32.880 --> 00:20:35.990
that its integral from some
point to another point,

00:20:35.990 --> 00:20:40.519
does not depend on what path
you integrate it on.

00:20:40.519 --> 00:20:42.859
In other words,
you can take that path,

00:20:42.859 --> 00:20:46.309
break it up into segments
dr, and on each segment,

00:20:46.309 --> 00:20:48.220
the force is some variable.
 

00:20:48.220 --> 00:20:51.003
You take F⋅dr
of that little segment,

00:20:51.003 --> 00:20:53.635
add it up over all the segments
and make the segments

00:20:53.635 --> 00:20:54.750
vanishingly small.
 

00:20:54.750 --> 00:20:56.818
That's the meaning of this
integral.

00:20:56.818 --> 00:21:00.375
And you're supposed to get the
same answer, no matter what you

00:21:00.375 --> 00:21:03.288
do, including going like this,
or anything else.

00:21:03.288 --> 00:21:06.759
How can they all give the same
answer?

00:21:06.759 --> 00:21:10.795
In fact, I'll give you a simple
example where it's simply not

00:21:10.795 --> 00:21:13.618
true, so the answer depends on
the path.

00:21:13.618 --> 00:21:17.131
In fact, just about any force
you pick randomly will not have

00:21:17.131 --> 00:21:19.588
the property,
the answer does not depend on

00:21:19.588 --> 00:21:20.348
the path.
 

00:21:20.348 --> 00:21:23.769
Answers typically will depend
on what path you take.

00:21:23.769 --> 00:21:28.808
So let's take a simple force,
F =

00:21:28.808 --> 00:21:31.568
iy.
 

00:21:31.568 --> 00:21:34.448
I can think of more complicated
ones, but I don't have time to

00:21:34.448 --> 00:21:34.920
do them.
 

00:21:34.920 --> 00:21:37.650
So here's a simple one - force
depends on position.

00:21:37.650 --> 00:21:40.675
It points in the x
direction only and it grows with

00:21:40.675 --> 00:21:41.259
y.
 

00:21:41.259 --> 00:21:43.480
And I'm going to do two
calculations.

00:21:43.480 --> 00:21:48.065
I'm going to find the integral
from the origin to the point

00:21:48.065 --> 00:21:52.730
(1,1) first by going this way
and then by going that way.

00:21:52.730 --> 00:21:54.690
They are two possible paths.
 

00:21:54.690 --> 00:21:57.824
And you will see,
when I do the calculation,

00:21:57.824 --> 00:21:59.720
the answer is different.
 

00:21:59.720 --> 00:22:02.922
Therefore you cannot write the
answer as a difference of

00:22:02.922 --> 00:22:06.082
something here - something here,
because the answer is not a

00:22:06.082 --> 00:22:08.160
function only of the starting
and ending points,

00:22:08.160 --> 00:22:09.930
but how you got there.
 

00:22:09.930 --> 00:22:15.487
And I want to do this just to
remind you how to do these

00:22:15.487 --> 00:22:16.700
integrals.
 

00:22:16.700 --> 00:22:22.000
So let's take this segment here.
 

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:23.700
What is the work done?
 

00:22:23.700 --> 00:22:29.088
The work is the force which is
i times y times

00:22:29.088 --> 00:22:30.460
the distance.
 

00:22:30.460 --> 00:22:34.428
If you move horizontally,
perhaps you guys can see

00:22:34.428 --> 00:22:39.529
dr for a tiny segment
simply i times dx.

00:22:39.529 --> 00:22:42.609
And x goes from 0 to 1.
 

00:22:42.609 --> 00:22:47.789
So how much is that?
 

00:22:47.789 --> 00:22:50.269
Can you do this?
 

00:22:50.269 --> 00:22:51.930
I want the first person who
knows the answer.

00:22:51.930 --> 00:22:52.529
Yes?
 

00:22:52.529 --> 00:22:55.130
Student:  Zero
______________.

00:22:55.130 --> 00:22:55.619
Prof: Right.
 

00:22:55.619 --> 00:22:58.538
On this line, y is 0.
 

00:22:58.538 --> 00:23:00.441
In fact, if you draw a picture
of the force,

00:23:00.441 --> 00:23:01.368
it looks like this.
 

00:23:01.368 --> 00:23:04.500
It gets bigger and bigger and
bigger as you go further off.

00:23:04.500 --> 00:23:06.980
And if you go to negative
values, it looks like this.

00:23:06.980 --> 00:23:09.319
So there is no y,
there is no force.

00:23:09.319 --> 00:23:11.660
That is 0.
 

00:23:11.660 --> 00:23:15.132
If you go to this segment,
y is definitely

00:23:15.132 --> 00:23:17.454
non-zero,
but notice, the force is like

00:23:17.454 --> 00:23:20.266
this and the dr is in the
y direction and they are

00:23:20.266 --> 00:23:24.660
perpendicular,
so the dot product is 0.

00:23:24.660 --> 00:23:25.630
Okay?
 

00:23:25.630 --> 00:23:28.108
dr and F are
perpendicular.

00:23:28.108 --> 00:23:31.000
One is along i and one
is along j dot product to

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:31.190
0.
 

00:23:31.190 --> 00:23:35.130
If you take this path,
the work done is 0.

00:23:35.130 --> 00:23:38.924
Now let's take the other path,
go like this and then like

00:23:38.924 --> 00:23:39.400
this.
 

00:23:39.400 --> 00:23:41.720
On this section,
we have the same problem.

00:23:41.720 --> 00:23:42.779
Force is to the right.
 

00:23:42.779 --> 00:23:44.140
You're moving straight up.
 

00:23:44.140 --> 00:23:47.269
dr and F are
perpendicular.

00:23:47.269 --> 00:23:50.368
But on the last segment,
from here to here,

00:23:50.368 --> 00:23:52.375
you get a non-zero
contribution,

00:23:52.375 --> 00:23:54.769
because force is
iy,

00:23:54.769 --> 00:23:58.930
displacement is
idx and x

00:23:58.930 --> 00:24:02.846
goes from 0 to 1,
and y is frozen at the

00:24:02.846 --> 00:24:05.690
value 1,
because you're on this line.

00:24:05.690 --> 00:24:06.930
Frozen at the value 1.
 

00:24:06.930 --> 00:24:08.240
Just put 1 for it.
 

00:24:08.240 --> 00:24:12.338
And i⋅i is
1, integral of dx is 1.

00:24:12.338 --> 00:24:15.709
Therefore the work done by the
force going up and then to the

00:24:15.709 --> 00:24:16.440
right is 1.
 

00:24:16.440 --> 00:24:20.318
Going to the right and then up
is 0.

00:24:20.318 --> 00:24:23.598
You can take other paths and
keep getting other answers.

00:24:23.598 --> 00:24:25.519
So this is a force for which
it's not true,

00:24:25.519 --> 00:24:29.172
and I bet you that if you just
randomly selected forces in the

00:24:29.172 --> 00:24:32.355
2 dimensional plane,
they will never have the

00:24:32.355 --> 00:24:35.970
property that the integral is
path independent.

00:24:35.970 --> 00:24:39.733
So it looks like we are onto a
hopeless task,

00:24:39.733 --> 00:24:43.500
that the answer cannot depend
on the path.

00:24:43.500 --> 00:24:47.635
So maybe there is no problem in
which you can derive a law of

00:24:47.635 --> 00:24:49.358
conservation of energy.
 

00:24:49.358 --> 00:24:53.555
Of course, you guys know,
you can derive a law of

00:24:53.555 --> 00:24:57.750
conservation of energy for a
family of forces.

00:24:57.750 --> 00:25:00.291
In fact, the answer is,
there's an infinite of numbers

00:25:00.291 --> 00:25:02.740
of forces you can devise for
which this is true,

00:25:02.740 --> 00:25:06.910
namely, the answer does not
depend on the path.

00:25:06.910 --> 00:25:10.348
Before writing those forces,
let me explain to you one other

00:25:10.348 --> 00:25:12.038
way to write the condition.
 

00:25:12.038 --> 00:25:15.980
The condition,
namely of a conservative force,

00:25:15.980 --> 00:25:18.530
is that the integral from here
to here is the same as the

00:25:18.530 --> 00:25:23.212
integral from there to there,
from 1 to 2 along path A

00:25:23.212 --> 00:25:26.538
and 1 to 2 along path B.
 

00:25:26.538 --> 00:25:30.570
They must be equal for any
starting point and any ending

00:25:30.570 --> 00:25:33.430
point and any two paths joining
them.

00:25:33.430 --> 00:25:39.925
So what I'm saying is,
F⋅dr from 1

00:25:39.925 --> 00:25:47.421
to 2 along A = integral
F⋅dr from 1

00:25:47.421 --> 00:25:50.420
to 2 along B.
 

00:25:50.420 --> 00:25:56.203
Let me rewrite this by putting
a - sign here and equate it to

00:25:56.203 --> 00:25:56.589
0.
 

00:25:56.589 --> 00:25:57.318
That's fine.
 

00:25:57.318 --> 00:26:00.390
Shifted it to the left hand
side.

00:26:00.390 --> 00:26:04.220
But then we use the fact that
when you go from 1 to 2,

00:26:04.220 --> 00:26:09.034
with a - sign,
this second guy is same as from

00:26:09.034 --> 00:26:14.490
2 to 1 along B of
F⋅dr.

00:26:14.490 --> 00:26:16.939
In other words,
the line integral going this

00:26:16.939 --> 00:26:19.558
way is - the line integral going
backwards,

00:26:19.558 --> 00:26:22.141
because at every step,
dr is opposite but F

00:26:22.141 --> 00:26:25.690
is the same at the point,
F⋅dr changes

00:26:25.690 --> 00:26:26.068
sign.
 

00:26:26.068 --> 00:26:30.670
Therefore it tells you then
that the line integral from here

00:26:30.670 --> 00:26:32.618
to there and back is 0.
 

00:26:32.618 --> 00:26:36.275
We write that by saying the
