00:35:00.177 --> 00:35:00.590
right?
 

00:35:00.590 --> 00:35:06.289
The change in the function
f is df/dx

00:35:06.289 --> 00:35:08.090
times dx.
 

00:35:08.090 --> 00:35:11.019
There are other changes
proportional to dx^(3)

00:35:11.019 --> 00:35:13.385
and dx^(2),
but for small dx,

00:35:13.385 --> 00:35:14.570
that's all it is.
 

00:35:14.570 --> 00:35:16.329
That's the meaning of the rate
of change.

00:35:16.329 --> 00:35:20.228
If you multiply the rate of
change by the change you get a

00:35:20.228 --> 00:35:21.940
change in the function.
 

00:35:21.940 --> 00:35:25.106
If you're in 2 dimensions,
if you move from one point to

00:35:25.106 --> 00:35:27.639
another point,
you've got a function U

00:35:27.639 --> 00:35:30.230
that depends on x and on
y.

00:35:30.230 --> 00:35:32.952
Therefore it changes,
because you change x and

00:35:32.952 --> 00:35:35.099
it changes because you change
y.

00:35:35.099 --> 00:35:37.260
It's changing because of two
reasons.

00:35:37.260 --> 00:35:38.929
This is the change due to
change in x;

00:35:38.929 --> 00:35:41.349
that's the change due to change
in y.

00:35:41.349 --> 00:35:44.114
For very small,
infinitesimal dx and

00:35:44.114 --> 00:35:46.219
dy, that is the change.
 

00:35:46.219 --> 00:35:54.409
That is just the change in the
function U.

00:35:54.409 --> 00:35:57.239
It follows then that if you add
up all these

00:35:57.239 --> 00:36:03.489
F⋅dr's from
