00:36:03.489 --> 00:36:08.510
me U_1 -
U_2.

00:36:08.510 --> 00:36:15.530
Therefore integral
F⋅dr from 1

00:36:15.530 --> 00:36:23.429
to 2 is U_1 -
U_2.

00:36:23.429 --> 00:36:26.503
So the magic is the following -
you pick a function U,

00:36:26.503 --> 00:36:29.014
you can think of the function
U as measured

00:36:29.014 --> 00:36:30.860
perpendicular to the blackboard.
 

00:36:30.860 --> 00:36:33.849
It's like a height or something
coming out of the blackboard.

00:36:33.849 --> 00:36:37.447
You cooked up a force which is
related to the rate of change of

00:36:37.447 --> 00:36:39.757
the function U,
so that if you add all the

00:36:39.757 --> 00:36:42.597
F⋅dr`s,
you're getting the change in

00:36:42.597 --> 00:36:44.860
the function between two points.
 

00:36:44.860 --> 00:36:48.414
And that change in the function
is independent of how you got

00:36:48.414 --> 00:36:48.889
there.
 

00:36:48.889 --> 00:36:51.650
Think of U as a height
of a mountain,

00:36:51.650 --> 00:36:54.219
sitting on top of the xy
plane.

00:36:54.219 --> 00:36:56.516
Then F is really
proportional to the rate of

00:36:56.516 --> 00:36:58.309
change of the height of the
mountain.

00:36:58.309 --> 00:37:00.644
And F⋅dr is
the change when you move a

00:37:00.644 --> 00:37:02.730
distance dr,
a vector distance dr.

00:37:02.730 --> 00:37:05.250
You add all the changes,
what are you adding?

00:37:05.250 --> 00:37:07.679
You're adding the height,
your elevation.

00:37:07.679 --> 00:37:10.197
And when you're done,
