00:37:10.197 --> 00:37:13.159
difference between the final
point and the starting point.

00:37:13.159 --> 00:37:15.659
It doesn't depend on how you
climb that mountain.

00:37:15.659 --> 00:37:18.018
You can take a long path,
you can take a short path.

00:37:18.018 --> 00:37:22.304
As long as you're keeping track
of how many feet have I climbed,

00:37:22.304 --> 00:37:24.889
you're going to get only one
answer.

00:37:24.889 --> 00:37:28.172
So not every F has this
property, but an F

00:37:28.172 --> 00:37:31.815
derived from U by that
trick of taking the gradient has

00:37:31.815 --> 00:37:32.889
this property.
 

00:37:32.889 --> 00:37:38.061
Therefore for that F,
you might say this is for

00:37:38.061 --> 00:37:40.110
conservative force.
 

00:37:40.110 --> 00:37:41.840
But we always knew
F⋅dr is

00:37:41.840 --> 00:37:43.690
K_2 -
K_1,

00:37:43.690 --> 00:37:46.818
therefore we get
K_1

00:37:46.818 --> 00:37:50.556
U_1 =
K_2 

00:37:50.556 --> 00:37:52.730
U_2.
 

00:37:52.730 --> 00:37:56.150
In other words,
the U that you began

00:37:56.150 --> 00:38:00.059
with is the potential energy for
that problem.

00:38:00.059 --> 00:38:04.670
So what you're manufacturing is
pairs of potentials and forces.

00:38:04.670 --> 00:38:07.280
For every U that you
dream up, there's a force,

00:38:07.280 --> 00:38:10.039
which is obtained by gradient,
- gradient of U.

00:38:10.039 --> 00:38:13.034
And in that problem,
where that force is acting on

00:38:13.034 --> 00:38:15.067
particles,
the energy that is conserved

00:38:15.067 --> 00:38:18.148
will be the kinetic,
the function U at the

00:38:18.148 --> 00:38:22.385
starting point,
will be equal to kinetic plus

00:38:22.385 --> 00:38:25.239
potential at the end point.
 

00:38:25.239 --> 00:38:29.061
And the interesting thing is,
there are no other conservative

00:38:29.061 --> 00:38:32.690
forces, except forces you can
get by taking a U and

00:38:32.690 --> 00:38:34.219
taking its gradient.
 

00:38:34.219 --> 00:38:38.119
So all conservative forces fall
under this category,

00:38:38.119 --> 00:38:42.387
and they all have a conserved
quantity where the potential

00:38:42.387 --> 00:38:46.880
energy is the U from
which the F is derived.

00:38:46.880 --> 00:38:51.956
So we can say it as follows -
F = - gradient of

00:38:51.956 --> 00:38:53.010
U.
 

00:38:53.010 --> 00:38:55.543
The gradient is the combination
of i times the x

00:38:55.543 --> 00:38:57.364
derivative and j
times the y

00:38:57.364 --> 00:38:58.210
derivative.
 

00:38:58.210 --> 00:39:03.811
And U at 2 - U at
1 is - integral

00:39:03.811 --> 00:39:08.440
F⋅dr from 1
to 2.

00:39:08.440 --> 00:39:13.472
This is the 2 dimensional
generalization of something I

00:39:13.472 --> 00:39:16.550
wrote in 1 dimension somewhere.
 

00:39:16.550 --> 00:39:18.449
Oh, way on the top.
 

00:39:18.449 --> 00:39:20.356
Here, F = - dU
/dx,

00:39:20.356 --> 00:39:22.166
U(x_2)
−

00:39:22.166 --> 00:39:25.150
U(x_1)
is - integral of F.

00:39:25.150 --> 00:39:28.840
The only difference is the
integrand has become this

00:39:28.840 --> 00:39:31.663
F⋅dr,
rather than the

00:39:31.663 --> 00:39:33.690
F_x dx.
 

00:39:33.690 --> 00:39:37.000
So you can get conservation of
energy in higher dimensions for

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:39.280
those forces that come from a
potential.

00:39:39.280 --> 00:39:43.949
U is called a potential.
 

00:39:43.949 --> 00:39:53.199
U is called a potential
energy.

00:39:53.199 --> 00:39:59.355
So now we can ask the following
