00:40:06.090 --> 00:40:06.940
Now there are two options.
 

00:40:06.940 --> 00:40:09.623
One is, you are so smart,
you can look at the function

00:40:09.623 --> 00:40:12.114
and say,
"Hey, this is the gradient

00:40:12.114 --> 00:40:14.550
of some other function
U."

00:40:14.550 --> 00:40:15.713
If you do that,
then you are done,

00:40:15.713 --> 00:40:17.300
because if it's the gradient of
some function,

00:40:17.300 --> 00:40:18.360
we know it's conservative.
 

00:40:18.360 --> 00:40:21.599
But what if you cannot see that
right away?

00:40:21.599 --> 00:40:23.820
With simple polynomials,
you can easily guess.

00:40:23.820 --> 00:40:26.403
Like the example I gave you,
if F_x is

00:40:26.403 --> 00:40:28.898
-3x^(2)y^(2),
F_y is

00:40:28.898 --> 00:40:31.574
-2x^(3)y,
maybe you can guess that U

00:40:31.574 --> 00:40:33.309
is x^(3)y^(2).
 

00:40:33.309 --> 00:40:36.601
But for more complicated
functions, you won't be able to

00:40:36.601 --> 00:40:37.079
do it.
 

00:40:37.079 --> 00:40:40.668
So there's a process for
testing any force to see if it's

00:40:40.668 --> 00:40:41.630
conservative.
 

00:40:41.630 --> 00:40:43.429
And the process is the
following.

00:40:43.429 --> 00:40:46.554
It argues as follows -
F_x is

00:40:46.554 --> 00:40:48.570
−dU/dx.
 

00:40:48.570 --> 00:40:53.849
F_y is
-dU/dy.

00:40:53.849 --> 00:40:56.967
Then consider
dF_x /

00:40:56.967 --> 00:41:01.210
dy, which is
-d^(2)U/dydx.

00:41:01.210 --> 00:41:03.945
Then consider
dF_y /

00:41:03.945 --> 00:41:07.670
dx, which is
-d^(2)U/dxdy.

00:41:07.670 --> 00:41:10.420
And it's the property of
partial derivatives that the

00:41:10.420 --> 00:41:13.914
cross derivative,
second cross derivative,

00:41:13.914 --> 00:41:20.309
is independent of whether you
take dydx or dxdy.

00:41:20.309 --> 00:41:28.420
So let's go to our test case,
U = x^(3)y^(2).

00:41:28.420 --> 00:41:34.083
dU/dx =
3x^(2)y^(2) and

00:41:34.083 --> 00:41:39.219
dU/dy =
2x^(3)y.

00:41:39.219 --> 00:41:41.242
Now I'm saying,
take the x derivative of

00:41:41.242 --> 00:41:42.429
this y derivative.
 

00:41:42.429 --> 00:41:46.039
That's written as
d^(2)U/dydx.

00:41:46.039 --> 00:41:49.210
y derivative of the
x derivative gives me

00:41:49.210 --> 00:41:50.210
6x^(2)y.
 

00:41:50.210 --> 00:41:52.860
Then I say take the x
derivative of the y

00:41:52.860 --> 00:41:53.500
derivative.
 

00:41:53.500 --> 00:41:55.940
This gives me 3x^(2).
 

00:41:55.940 --> 00:42:01.110
That means 6x^(2)y.
 

00:42:01.110 --> 00:42:03.280
So cross derivatives are always
equal.

00:42:03.280 --> 00:42:04.268
Yes?
 

00:42:04.268 --> 00:42:05.846
Student:  Is this
_______ if we're going ________

00:42:05.846 --> 00:42:06.420
taking __________?
 

00:42:06.420 --> 00:42:08.840
Prof: Yes,
that's correct.

00:42:08.840 --> 00:42:12.146
So in 2 dimensions,
this is the only test you have

00:42:12.146 --> 00:42:12.889
to apply.
 

00:42:12.889 --> 00:42:16.469
The test you have to apply is,
are the cross derivatives of

00:42:16.469 --> 00:42:17.579
the force equal?
 

00:42:17.579 --> 00:42:19.824
Namely, is the y
derivative of the force

00:42:19.824 --> 00:42:22.119
F_x = to x
derivative of

00:42:22.119 --> 00:42:23.340
F_y?
 

00:42:23.340 --> 00:42:28.967
You want to see if
dF_x/dy

00:42:28.967 --> 00:42:32.300
= dF_y/dx.
 

00:42:32.300 --> 00:42:34.630
If that is true,
it is conservative.

00:42:34.630 --> 00:42:37.893
And it comes from the fact that
if F is the derivative of

00:42:37.893 --> 00:42:41.054
some function U,
then this mix derivative being

00:42:41.054 --> 00:42:42.989
equal is a diagnostic for that.
 

00:42:42.989 --> 00:42:46.030
In 3 dimensions,
there are 2 more equations.

00:42:46.030 --> 00:42:48.525
We're not going to use them,
but I'll just mention what they

00:42:48.525 --> 00:42:48.780
are.
 

00:42:48.780 --> 00:42:51.690
You get that by moving every
index 1 notch.

00:42:51.690 --> 00:42:54.396
So this x goes to
y, this y goes to

00:42:54.396 --> 00:42:57.449
z, this y goes to
z, this x goes to

00:42:57.449 --> 00:42:58.090
y.
 

00:42:58.090 --> 00:42:59.800
There's one more condition.
 

00:42:59.800 --> 00:43:03.829
And another condition,
z goes back to x,

00:43:03.829 --> 00:43:07.239
x goes z--let's
see, y goes to z,

00:43:07.239 --> 00:43:11.103
z goes to x =
dF_x/

00:43:11.103 --> 00:43:12.050
dz.
 

00:43:12.050 --> 00:43:15.744
I'm not worried about whether
you write this down or not,

00:43:15.744 --> 00:43:19.835
but I do want you to know in 2
dimensions, you have to remember

00:43:19.835 --> 00:43:21.090
this condition.
 

00:43:21.090 --> 00:43:25.795
So this mathematic extends to
all dimensions,

00:43:25.795 --> 00:43:29.860
but I'm doing it for the case
of 2D.

00:43:29.860 --> 00:43:33.809
So let's take stock of what has
been done.

00:43:33.809 --> 00:43:38.068
What has been done is to think
from scratch on how to get the

00:43:38.068 --> 00:43:41.690
law of conservation of energy in
high dimensions.

00:43:41.690 --> 00:43:43.679
You start with the kinetic
energy and you ask,

00:43:43.679 --> 00:43:44.610
why does it change?
 

00:43:44.610 --> 00:43:47.554
And you find it changes due to
the force, and you find the

00:43:47.554 --> 00:43:50.190
change in kinetic energy is the
line integral of

00:43:50.190 --> 00:43:53.119
F⋅dr from
start to finish.

00:43:53.119 --> 00:43:56.079
But that doesn't give you a
work energy--

00:43:56.079 --> 00:43:57.909
it gives you a work energy
theorem,

00:43:57.909 --> 00:43:59.590
but not a law of conservation
of energy,

00:43:59.590 --> 00:44:02.760
because this integral can
depend on the path.

00:44:02.760 --> 00:44:04.864
Then you say,
maybe there are some functions

00:44:04.864 --> 00:44:07.510
for which the answer depends
only on the end points.

00:44:07.510 --> 00:44:09.469
Then we get a law of
conservation of energy,

00:44:09.469 --> 00:44:13.626
and we found out that we can
manufacture such functions at

00:44:13.626 --> 00:44:15.411
will,
by taking any function of

00:44:15.411 --> 00:44:18.878
U,
taking its gradient,

00:44:18.878 --> 00:44:21.670
or - the gradient.
 

00:44:21.670 --> 00:44:25.222
Therefore that's a way to
generate conservative forces and

00:44:25.222 --> 00:44:28.340
they are the only conservative
forces there are.

00:44:28.340 --> 00:44:30.963
There's no other conservative
forces which are not gradients

00:44:30.963 --> 00:44:31.630
of something.
 

00:44:31.630 --> 00:44:34.481
And the relation between the
potential and the force,

00:44:34.481 --> 00:44:35.690
you should know now.
 

00:44:35.690 --> 00:44:39.119
It's what you learned in 1D,
suitably generalized to higher

00:44:39.119 --> 00:44:39.889
dimensions.
 

00:44:39.889 --> 00:44:43.523
Change in potential is this and
the forces obtained from the

00:44:43.523 --> 00:44:45.739
potential by taking the
gradient,

00:44:45.739 --> 00:44:50.449
the change in potential is
obtained by integrating the

00:44:50.449 --> 00:44:51.159
force.
 

00:44:51.159 --> 00:44:53.780
If you ever get confused about
sign and - sign and so on,

00:44:53.780 --> 00:44:55.760
go back to the harmonic
oscillator,

00:44:55.760 --> 00:45:06.710
for which the thing is 1
over--is kx^(2)/2.

00:45:06.710 --> 00:45:13.655
So let me give you one simple
example that we all know,

00:45:13.655 --> 00:45:19.699
which is the force of gravity
near the earth.

00:45:19.699 --> 00:45:25.414
So here is the earth,
so there is some x and

00:45:25.414 --> 00:45:30.559
y coordinates,
and here is z.

00:45:30.559 --> 00:45:33.893
So I might as well write down
the answer, because you guys all

00:45:33.893 --> 00:45:34.550
know this.
 

00:45:34.550 --> 00:45:41.637
U for gravity is
mg times z. And

00:45:41.637 --> 00:45:45.677
the force of gravity,
which is

00:45:45.677 --> 00:45:51.539
-idu/dx -
jdu/dy,

00:45:51.539 --> 00:45:56.556
- kdu/dz,
all you got here is

00:45:56.556 --> 00:45:59.728
-kmg,
because it doesn't depend on

00:45:59.728 --> 00:46:01.400
x,
it doesn't depend on y.

00:46:01.400 --> 00:46:03.670
It depends only on z and
the z derivative is

00:46:03.670 --> 00:46:04.070
trivial.
 

00:46:04.070 --> 00:46:11.400
Force is -mg pointing
down.

00:46:11.400 --> 00:46:14.599
So the force is the gradient of
the potential and you can ask,

00:46:14.599 --> 00:46:17.780
is the potential difference
between two points,

00:46:17.780 --> 00:46:20.610
U_2 -
U_1,

00:46:20.610 --> 00:46:26.280
is it equal to integral of
F⋅dr from 1

00:46:26.280 --> 00:46:26.989
to 2?
 

00:46:26.989 --> 00:46:28.570
You can easily check that.
 

00:46:28.570 --> 00:46:34.255
If you go from here to here,
straight up,

00:46:34.255 --> 00:46:42.784
then the integral of -mg
times dz from start to

00:46:42.784 --> 00:46:49.750
finish, with a - sign is just
mgz - 0.

00:46:49.750 --> 00:46:51.440
So indeed, it is true.
 

00:46:51.440 --> 00:46:53.610
And if you took two points,
not on top of each other,

00:46:53.610 --> 00:46:56.280
but something like this,
you can always do the integral

00:46:56.280 --> 00:46:58.523
from here to here,
where there's no change in

00:46:58.523 --> 00:47:00.722
potential,
and do the integral there,

00:47:00.722 --> 00:47:02.809
which will give the same
answer.

00:47:02.809 --> 00:47:06.581
So gravity's a very trivial
example, a very easy case,

00:47:06.581 --> 00:47:10.068
but you can see that
gravitation is a conservative

00:47:10.068 --> 00:47:10.780
force.
 

00:47:10.780 --> 00:47:12.630
And you can see why it's a
conservative force,

00:47:12.630 --> 00:47:16.659
because if you took a path
where you went like this,

00:47:16.659 --> 00:47:20.347
let's say, and you went like
this, where you get the same

00:47:20.347 --> 00:47:22.059
answer as here and here.
 

00:47:22.059 --> 00:47:26.074
Because in this path and this
path, you don't do any work,

00:47:26.074 --> 00:47:29.454
because F and dr
are perpendicular,

00:47:29.454 --> 00:47:30.159
right?
 

00:47:30.159 --> 00:47:32.193
F is like this,
and the displacement is like

00:47:32.193 --> 00:47:34.101
that,
and it's the same thing,

00:47:34.101 --> 00:47:36.541
whereas here,
if you go like this,

00:47:36.541 --> 00:47:39.518
F is down and dr
is down,

00:47:39.518 --> 00:47:41.210
F is down,
dr is down,

00:47:41.210 --> 00:47:43.969
and it's the same F here
and here;

00:47:43.969 --> 00:47:48.400
are the same height so you get
the same answer.

00:47:48.400 --> 00:47:52.483
Okay, but now,
why did we spend quite a bit of

00:47:52.483 --> 00:47:57.474
time on conservative forces,
because that's not what the

00:47:57.474 --> 00:47:59.380
primary focus is?
 

00:47:59.380 --> 00:48:01.860
It was electricity and
electrostatics.

00:48:01.860 --> 00:48:06.025
So we've got to ask ourselves,
does the electrostatic force

00:48:06.025 --> 00:48:08.900
meet the test of a conservative
force?

00:48:08.900 --> 00:48:11.619
Well, we know it will,
because otherwise I wouldn't

00:48:11.619 --> 00:48:14.340
have spent this much time
building up the stuff.

00:48:14.340 --> 00:48:17.809
But let's just verify that.
 

00:48:17.809 --> 00:48:20.469
It looks like a very formidable
task.

00:48:20.469 --> 00:48:23.268
Let's see why it's a formidable
task to verify it's

00:48:23.268 --> 00:48:24.110
conservative.
 

00:48:24.110 --> 00:48:27.797
I'm claiming that you've got
all kinds of these charges

00:48:27.797 --> 00:48:31.556
producing a field here and I
want to prove that the line

00:48:31.556 --> 00:48:35.039
integral of this force on any
closed loop is 0.

00:48:35.039 --> 00:48:39.373
Or I want to prove the integral
on one path is the integral on

00:48:39.373 --> 00:48:42.498
any other path,
for any 2 paths between any 2

00:48:42.498 --> 00:48:43.280
points.
 

00:48:43.280 --> 00:48:48.650
I don't have time to show all
that, right?

00:48:48.650 --> 00:48:51.750
If the theorem is wrong,
do you agree it may not be so

00:48:51.750 --> 00:48:52.920
hard to show that?
 

00:48:52.920 --> 00:48:56.039
What will it take to show it is
not conservative?

00:48:56.039 --> 00:48:57.159
Yes?
 

00:48:57.159 --> 00:48:59.119
Student:  Just 2 paths
for which the integral is not

00:48:59.119 --> 00:48:59.389
equal.
 

00:48:59.389 --> 00:48:59.909
Prof: Yes.
 

00:48:59.909 --> 00:49:03.543
If you pick any 2 paths,
should be the same end points,

00:49:03.543 --> 00:49:06.840
so always the integral is not
equal, that's it.

00:49:06.840 --> 00:49:09.818
But the fact that they were
equal doesn't mean that somebody

00:49:09.818 --> 00:49:12.547
else will not find some other
two paths with some other

00:49:12.547 --> 00:49:14.820
starting points which they are
not equal.

00:49:14.820 --> 00:49:16.250
So how are we going to do this?
 

00:49:16.250 --> 00:49:20.233
How are we going to test for
every configuration of electric

00:49:20.233 --> 00:49:23.610
field, every element of charges
is conservative?

00:49:23.610 --> 00:49:31.909
So what do you think a strategy
will be?

00:49:31.909 --> 00:49:32.900
Yes?
 

00:49:32.900 --> 00:49:34.309
Any ideas?
 

00:49:34.309 --> 00:49:36.827
How am I going to take all
possible charges and work it out

00:49:36.827 --> 00:49:37.349
each time?
 

00:49:37.349 --> 00:49:38.179
Yes?
 

00:49:38.179 --> 00:49:40.710
Student:  I guess you
could find the electric field

00:49:40.710 --> 00:49:42.489
and use that test to see--
Prof: Right,

00:49:42.489 --> 00:49:44.409
but to find the electric field
and see if it works,

00:49:44.409 --> 00:49:46.592
you have to calculate the
electric field as a function of

00:49:46.592 --> 00:49:48.733
x,
y and z for every

00:49:48.733 --> 00:49:50.030
arrangement of charges.
 

00:49:50.030 --> 00:49:51.847
Then you can ask,
is that true,

00:49:51.847 --> 00:49:53.059
those derivatives?
 

00:49:53.059 --> 00:49:53.650
Yes?
 

00:49:53.650 --> 00:49:55.144
Student:  But what works
for one charge should work for

00:49:55.144 --> 00:49:56.150
all charges, because of
supersposition.

00:49:56.150 --> 00:49:57.268
Prof: There we go.
 

00:49:57.268 --> 00:50:01.630
If it works for one charge,
it will work for any

00:50:01.630 --> 00:50:03.949
arrangement of charges.
 

00:50:03.949 --> 00:50:05.909
So you may not have appreciated
fully the power of

00:50:05.909 --> 00:50:07.389
superposition,
but you can see now.

00:50:07.389 --> 00:50:09.704
If you did not realize that,
the problem looks

00:50:09.704 --> 00:50:10.579
insurmountable.
 

00:50:10.579 --> 00:50:13.010
Who can handle every
arrangement of charges?

00:50:13.010 --> 00:50:16.467
But if charge by charge it is
true that the electric field due

00:50:16.467 --> 00:50:19.755
to charge 1 is conservative,
electric field due to charge 2

00:50:19.755 --> 00:50:20.889
is conservative.
 

00:50:20.889 --> 00:50:22.510
When I add them up,
the net field is

00:50:22.510 --> 00:50:24.550
E_1
E_2.

00:50:24.550 --> 00:50:26.327
The line integral of
E_1 E_2

00:50:26.327 --> 00:50:28.351
is the line integral
of E_1_

00:50:28.351 --> 00:50:30.199
 the line integral of
E_2.

00:50:30.199 --> 00:50:32.543
E_1 gives 0 on
any closed loop,

00:50:32.543 --> 00:50:34.489
other will give 0 on any closed
loop.

00:50:34.489 --> 00:50:36.909
The trick is going to be just
do it for one charge.

00:50:36.909 --> 00:50:38.119
That's it.
 

00:50:38.119 --> 00:50:41.159
If you can see it for one
charge, you get by superposition

00:50:41.159 --> 00:50:45.143
that it's true for any charge,
because the field is additive

00:50:45.143 --> 00:50:48.119
and the integral is additive,
okay.

00:50:48.119 --> 00:50:49.469
That's the two parts.
 

00:50:49.469 --> 00:50:51.327
If you've got charges,
the net e is

00:50:51.327 --> 00:50:53.320
E_1
E_2.

00:50:53.320 --> 00:50:54.943
The integral of
E_1 E_2

00:50:54.943 --> 00:50:56.777
is the integral of
E_1 the

00:50:56.777 --> 00:50:58.119
integral of
E_2.

00:50:58.119 --> 00:50:59.530
That's the way integrals work.
 

00:50:59.530 --> 00:51:02.579
If each one vanishes on a
closed loop, you're done.

00:51:02.579 --> 00:51:04.179
So I'm just going to take one
charge.

00:51:04.179 --> 00:51:10.610
Here's one charge and let me
draw for convenience all the

00:51:10.610 --> 00:51:14.170
field lines coming out of it.
 

00:51:14.170 --> 00:51:17.391
Then I want to see,
if I do a line integral,

00:51:17.391 --> 00:51:21.210
say from here to here,
will I get the same answer on

00:51:21.210 --> 00:51:22.710
some other path?
 

00:51:22.710 --> 00:51:26.329
Let's test that.
 

00:51:26.329 --> 00:51:29.780
So the first integral is from 1
to 2 on this path.

00:51:29.780 --> 00:51:31.670
Then I'm going to take another
one,

00:51:31.670 --> 00:51:34.222
which is different from it,
where you can see the answer is

00:51:34.222 --> 00:51:36.708
the same,
then go on making more and more

00:51:36.708 --> 00:51:39.989
changes,
and the answer will not change.

00:51:39.989 --> 00:51:45.280
So I'm going to take another
path where I go tangent to the

00:51:45.280 --> 00:51:47.469
lines, along a circle.
 

00:51:47.469 --> 00:51:52.295
Then I go here,
till I get to that radius,

00:51:52.295 --> 00:51:56.179
then I turn around and do that.
 

00:51:56.179 --> 00:52:01.525
I claim the integral will be
the same on this path,

00:52:01.525 --> 00:52:05.159
this one, that one and that
one.

00:52:05.159 --> 00:52:09.257
So I want you to think about
why it's going to be true,

00:52:09.257 --> 00:52:09.789
okay?
 

00:52:09.789 --> 00:52:12.429
Think of it,
why it's okay to do that.

00:52:12.429 --> 00:52:17.469
You've got a new path but it
doesn't make a difference.

00:52:17.469 --> 00:52:18.030
Ready?
 

00:52:18.030 --> 00:52:21.289
Tell you the answer now?
 

00:52:21.289 --> 00:52:26.190
How many people don't know why
it's true?

00:52:26.190 --> 00:52:28.480
So other people know why it's
true.

00:52:28.480 --> 00:52:31.309
I'm going to ask the other
people.

00:52:31.309 --> 00:52:33.349
Okay, why is it true?
 

00:52:33.349 --> 00:52:35.139
Student:  I raised my
hand.

00:52:35.139 --> 00:52:37.329
Prof: You raised your
hand.

00:52:37.329 --> 00:52:39.119
All right.
 

00:52:39.119 --> 00:52:39.639
Yes?
 

00:52:39.639 --> 00:52:41.757
Student:  It's true,
because when you're moving on

00:52:41.757 --> 00:52:43.516
the paths this way,
they're radial,

00:52:43.516 --> 00:52:46.302
